__data__.text: France has one of the lowest retirement ages for an industrialized country.
France spends more than most countries on pensions, with it amounting to almost 14% of economic output.
France's pension system is largely built on a "pay-as-you-go structure".
Both workers and employers are assessed mandatory payroll taxes that are used to fund retiree pensions in France.
The current system has enabled generations to retire with a guaranteed, state-backed pension.
France has one of the lowest rates of pensioners at risk of poverty.
The net pension replacement rate in France is 74%.
The net pension replacement rate is a measure of how effectively retirement income replaces prior earnings.
The OECD and EU averages for net pension replacement rate are lower than that of France.
Rising life expectancy has left the French pension system in an increasingly precarious state.
In 2000, there were 2.1 workers paying into the French pension system for every one retiree.
In 2020, the ratio of workers to retirees had fallen to 1.7.
In 2070, it is expected to drop to 1.2, according to official projections.
The cost of pensions has partially contributed to France's national debt rising to 112% of GDP.
This is one of the highest levels in the EU, higher than the UK and Germany.
In March 2023, Macron said that when he began working there were 10 million French pensioners and now there are 17 million.
Macron sought to gradually raise the legal age when workers can start collecting a pension by three months every year until it reaches 64 in 2030.
Macron has accelerated a previous change that increased the number of years that workers must pay into the system to get a full pension.
Macron abolished special pension rules that benefited workers in sectors like energy and transportation.
The retirement age was to be raised to 64 or 65, from 62.

In early January 2023, Prime Minister Élisabeth Borne spoke on FranceInfo radio about the government's intention to raise the retirement age to 65.
The government was open to exploring "other solutions" to balance the pensions system by 2030, showing flexibility on the proposal.
The policy was planned to be presented to cabinet on 23 January and debated in parliament in early February.

Article 49.3 of the French Constitution allows the government to bypass the National Assembly and force through bills without a vote.
Invoking Article 49.3 triggers a proviso that allows for no-confidence motions to be filed in the government.
The Guardian reported that, as of 14 March, President Emmanuel Macron had two options: broker deals with Les Républicains or force the bill through using Article 49.3.
Using Article 49.3 risks inflaming a volatile public mood and losing the subsequent no-confidence motion.
Ministers had stated that the government would not use Article 49.3, which is widely condemned as undemocratic.
Instead, the government engaged in negotiations to guarantee a majority in the lower house.
Union leaders warned that using Article 49.3 would lead to a hardening of opposition and escalate strikes.
On 16 March, Macron invoked Article 49.3, a surprise, last-minute decision due to uncertainty about support from lawmakers for a National Assembly vote.
The reform's coordination by all of France's trade unions is a rare show of unity.

Polls consistently show that the measures are unpopular, as is the use of Article 49.3 to enact them without a parliamentary vote in the National Assembly.

Dimitris Koutsoumpas, the General Secretary of the Communist Party of Greece, attended a rally in Paris on 23 March.
At the rally, Koutsoumpas expressed his solidarity with the struggle of the French people against anti-labor policies and anti-popular choices.
Koutsoumpas stated that the working people of France and Greece should ensure their own interests and not the interests and profits of the few.
The International Anthem was played over loudspeakers at the rally.
Railway workers and trade unionists were present at the rally and offered Koutsoumpas a "Friends of the Paris Commune" handkerchief.
